  "text": "The Rust compiler's type inference engine is built around three core components:\n\n1. **InferCtxt** (compiler/rustc_infer/src/infer/mod.rs): The main inference context struct that coordinates type and region inference. Located at line 231, it contains the TyCtxt, manages typing modes, handles region constraints, and controls whether region obligations should be considered. This is the central hub for all type inference operations.\n\n2. **FnCtxt** (compiler/rustc_hir_typeck/src/fn_ctxt/mod.rs): The function-level type checker that extends the root type checking context. Defined at line 44, it encapsulates function-specific type checking state including: the body being checked, parameter environment, return type coercion tracking, divergence analysis, and enclosing breakable contexts. FnCtxt works with InferCtxt to perform type inference during function body typechecking, as documented in its comments (lines 33-43).\n\n3. **TypeVariableOrigin** (compiler/rustc_infer/src/infer/type_variable.rs): A lightweight struct at line 93-100 that records the origin of type variables created during inference. It contains a span for error reporting and an optional param_def_id to track which type parameter (if any) a type variable was instantiated from, used primarily for diagnostic purposes.\n\nThese three components work together: InferCtxt provides the inference engine, FnCtxt applies it to function bodies with HIR-level context, and TypeVariableOrigin tracks type variable creation for better error messages."
}

